<div type="commentary"><!-- The plates had a ring, which was cut by the time Fleet saw it. The seal was also lost by that time. Or perhaps a seal was never attached, as the authenticity of the plates is questionable. The Telugu section may be in a different hand (compare especially the shape of ta in the two sections: in the Sanskrit it is the form found in earlier Cālukya plates, while in the Telugu it looks almost like the modern Telugu glyph). But I think it is more likely that it is the same hand, and probably a late one, who attempted to imitate an earlier style throughout the document, and to a greater extent in the Sanskrit section. In the Telugu section of the grant, I follow Fleet's readings and adopt his emendations unless otherwise indicated in the apparatus. Thus, in that section all editorial intervention encoded as a correction (including addition and suppression) follows Fleet's emendations, and all intervention encoded as a normalisation follows Fleet's tentative suggestions. In various spots, my scans of the plates are unclear, particularly on page 3r. It seems that in Fleet's notation, (?abc) means that "abc" may be the correct reading instead of that indicated before the parentheses, while (abc?) means a tentative emendation. I encode the former as unclear with @cert="low" or as a choice of two unclear items, as applicable.
--></div>



